value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;">Figure 1: Financial Capitalism</h1><h1 style="margin-top: 0px;"><p style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 400;">In the context of Industrial Capitalism, all debt is infinite because it is bound to production that has no determinable beginning or end. The amount of debt is calculated at year end, as previously described, from productivity levels. Although the debt can never be paid off, its finitude is enforced by reality. To increase this debt is to issue more shares, so funds can be transferred from other supply chains. Financial Capitalism breaks this connection with productive reality by also raising capital in the form of finite debt. In this context, each debt may be finite, but the capacity to issue such debt becomes bound by economic rather than productivity constraints, creating a crucible for the Financial Markets and its unbounded money supply.</p></h1>" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry height="120" width="760" x="20" y="500" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </root> </mxGraphModel> </diagram> <diagram id="QdAjD4QSt0dwQOu6Yf0B"
